Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 15th Weekly Dose of Optimism. For those tha=
t have this Monday off, enjoy the long weekend. Not Boring does not have of=
f and we=E2=80=99ll be in your inbox by 9am EST.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) An Interview With Daniel Gross and Nat Friedman About the Democratizati=
on of AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/598bf118-4ed7-4c31-aa49-4b5976bff7=
b8?r=3D9p0gt ]
Ben Thompson [ https://substack.com/redirect/68049c31-a632-4829-9b1b-9cd06f=
48b91d?r=3D9p0gt ] for Stratechery
The visual component of AI just arrests people so much more, even though we=
 already had GPT-3 and all those sorts of things. A picture is worth a thou=
sand words, it=E2=80=99s definitely the case as far as AI stuff goes, but t=
hey had all these controls, all these limitations, it was invite-only. It f=
ed into the assumption, the conventional wisdom =E2=80=94 which I held =E2=
=80=94 that AI is going to be this centralized thing, you need all this acc=
ess to data.
Then this summer happens [ https://substack.com/redirect/44ca44b0-0f9b-44fe=
-a823-237be78284ea?r=3D9p0gt ] and, first, Midjourney [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/00056768-faf5-46a1-8d65-aa7f2606c2ef?r=3D9p0gt ] comes along, an=
d it=E2=80=99s just from a user perspective a Discord server, and you can g=
enerate these amazing images for free =E2=80=94 we can get into the cost is=
sues in a little bit. Then the bomb drops, which is Stable Diffusion [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/4ba0dc1f-857d-48f6-a147-33bf283fc148?r=3D9p0gt ],=
 where now to go back to your open source thing, it=E2=80=99s this availabi=
lity and the iteration that we=E2=80=99ve seen even the last little bit has=
 been crazy and it=E2=80=99s been a real =E2=80=94 there=E2=80=99s an emoji=
 with the mind exploding (), that=E2=80=99s been me for the last two months=
=2E Every single assumption I had about t=
his space has feels like it=E2=80=99=
s been upset.
Seemingly everyday there=E2=80=99s a new AI release that captivates the att=
ention and imagination of the internet. It feels like we=E2=80=99re in the =
early Golden Days of Democratized AI and on the precipice of some major cha=
nges in the tech industry.
We=E2=80=99re not alone in feeling this way =E2=80=94 the movement has caug=
ht the attention of some of the most sophisticated people in tech. This con=
versation is among three such people: Ben Thompson [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/68049c31-a632-4829-9b1b-9cd06f48b91d?r=3D9p0gt ] (author of Stratec=
hery), Nat Friedman [ https://substack.com/redirect/9798b804-2d6b-4c65-9f04=
-cf3f52946b30?r=3D9p0gt ] (former CEO of GitHub, founder of AI Grant, and i=
nvestor), and Daniel Gross [ https://substack.com/redirect/73bc893c-6087-4e=
7c-8ba9-ede0f8a370db?r=3D9p0gt ] (founder of Cue, founder of YC=E2=80=99s A=
I program, and former Director working on ML projects at Apple).=20
This conversation is one of the more detailed but approachable I=E2=80=99ve=
 come across on how and why all of this progress in AI is happening, seemin=
gly overnight. It gives a good recent history of different approaches, expl=
anations of how they work, and an inside look at how Nat and the team at Gi=
tHub created CoPilot, the popular AI pair programmer. They make a fascinati=
ng observation, that the internet was only a necessary precursor =E2=80=94 =
we needed to digitize the world=E2=80=99s information for AI models to be a=
ble to learn from all of it =E2=80=94 and that the real progress, and defla=
tionary impact, is still to come.=20
(2) The Nobel Prize Announcements [ http://The 2022 Nobel Prize announcemen=
ts ]
We=E2=80=99re in Nobel Prize Season! Each weekday from Monday, October 3rd =
through Monday, October 10th, a Nobel Prize will be awarded to those who ha=
ve =E2=80=9Cconferred the greatest benefit to humankind.=E2=80=9D The six p=
rizes are awarded for work in Physics, Chemistry, Medicine, Literature, Pea=
ce, and Economic Sciences. As of writing, we=E2=80=99re five prizes in. Her=
e are brief summaries directly from the Nobel website:
Physics: Awarded to Alain Aspect [ https://substack.com/redirect/a75d5563-f=
a03-409b-bc8b-132fa4174cfd?r=3D9p0gt ], John F. Clauser [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/1498c82c-336c-4667-adbd-b127a25955a5?r=3D9p0gt ] and Anton Zei=
linger [ https://substack.com/redirect/3871d978-7c84-4b10-aab7-b617b6c29990=
?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=9Cfor experiments with entangled photons, establishing =
the violation of Bell inequalities and pioneering quantum information scien=
ce=E2=80=9D. Their results have cleared the way for new technology based up=
on quantum information.
Check out this Scientific American article [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
a9e5d26e-2103-48d3-b943-895a0454f66d?r=3D9p0gt ] (h/t Quinn Emmett [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/b27c82a6-a7fb-4ca3-aa29-d0553f17725d?r=3D9p0gt ]) f=
or a deeper and trippier explanation of this one.=20
Chemistry: Sometimes simple answers are the best. Barry Sharpless [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/6ec4c772-4bd4-4553-8a53-e0ae152f7969?r=3D9p0gt ] and=
 Morten Meldal [ https://substack.com/redirect/26a1ffa9-9897-4f8a-9429-1803=
c0f0ce39?r=3D9p0gt ] are awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2022 because =
they brought chemistry into the era of functionalism and laid the foundatio=
ns of click chemistry. They share the prize with Carolyn Bertozzi [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/a7f74057-778b-4b6a-86c4-28480c2b6866?r=3D9p0gt ], wh=
o took click chemistry to a new dimension and began using it to map cells. =
Her bioorthogonal reactions are now contributing to more targeted cancer tr=
eatments, among many other applications.
Commentary from Not Boring writer/investor Elliot Hershberg [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/1dfa8834-eb08-44a9-b1aa-3ea7a55e9664?r=3D9p0gt ] (who happ=
ens to work in Bertozzi=E2=80=99s building at Stanford): I'm really happy a=
bout this choice! The combination of click chemistry and bioorthogonal reac=
tions has been a massive unlock for labeling and measuring cells and biolog=
ical processes without disrupting them. As the names suggests, it lets you =
click together molecules in a much more modular and engineerable way, witho=
ut introducing toxicity to cells. It's great to see recognition for the val=
ue of tools/engineering in science!
Medicine: Svante P=C3=A4=C3=A4bo [ https://substack.com/redirect/aba38723-c=
254-4098-8b17-5444dd4e85d0?r=3D9p0gt ] accomplished something seemingly imp=
ossible: sequencing the genome of the Neanderthal, an extinct relative of p=
resent-day humans. He also made the sensational discovery of a previously u=
nknown hominin, Denisova. Importantly, P=C3=A4=C3=A4bo also found that gene=
 transfer had occurred from these now extinct hominins to Homo sapiens foll=
owing the migration out of Africa around 70,000 years ago. This ancient flo=
w of genes to present-day humans has physiological relevance today, for exa=
mple affecting how our immune system reacts to infections.
Literature: Awarded to the French author Annie Ernaux [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/cc35a178-4b2b-41d1-8611-c2888545885d?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=9Cfor th=
e courage and clinical acuity with which she uncovers the roots, estrangeme=
nts and collective restraints of personal memory.=E2=80=9D In her writing, =
Ernaux consistently and from different angles, examines a life marked by st=
rong disparities regarding gender, language and class. Her path to authorsh=
ip was long and arduous.
Peace:The 2022 Nobel Peace Prize is awarded to human rights advocate Ales B=
ialiatski [ https://substack.com/redirect/8a0695a1-f86a-49c4-a601-5e903227d=
c57?r=3D9p0gt ] from Belarus, the Russian human rights organisation Memoria=
l  [ https://substack.com/redirect/05ccf8e7-fe95-49e3-bf8c-0528b2b7e746?r=
=3D9p0gt ]and the Ukrainian human rights organisation Center for Civil Libe=
rties [ https://substack.com/redirect/1ef008cb-0876-4540-87b7-951b6fd06a87?=
r=3D9p0gt ].
Humans can be wicked smaht. We can do and discover things sacks of meat and=
 chemicals have no business doing and discovering. This year=E2=80=99s winn=
ers are a great reminder of that.
(3) At Long Last, Can Malaria Be Eradicated? [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/f9b7f754-d1af-4f4a-bf92-56b82b2c0596?r=3D9p0gt ]
Apoorva Mandavilli [ https://substack.com/redirect/31ddfc0a-9ebb-40d8-8c7f-=
a5aa4ce4871c?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
=E2=80=9CI think there=E2=80=99s so much room for optimism,=E2=80=9D said P=
hilip Welkhoff, director for malaria programs at the Bill and Melinda Gates=
 Foundation. =E2=80=9CLater this decade, we could actually launch a push th=
at gets us all the way to zero.=E2=80=9D
The medical and philanthropic worlds have been making progress in the fight=
 against malaria for decades, with treatments becoming more efficacious and=
 widely distributed. While malaria still causes over 600,000 deaths per yea=
r, mostly of young children in sub-Saharan African, there is hope that a fl=
urry of new vaccines could completely eradicate the disease in the coming y=
ears.
This one hits close to home: my sister, Meghan [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/1b5ba392-fd69-46eb-8c98-85f082c4c34a?r=3D9p0gt ], who lives in Accra, G=
hana and travels throughout the African continent, was infected with a rath=
er serious case of malaria this summer and spent weeks in the hospital. Luc=
kily, when the symptoms hit, she happened to be traveling in the UK, where =
the health system is far more advanced than those in areas where most malar=
ia patients live. So while these medical advances will go a long way toward=
s lowering the quantity and riskiness of each case, true eradication can on=
ly happen when the treatments are widely distributed into the communities t=
hat are the hardest to reach.
(4) The Ice Bucket Challenge wasn't just for social media. It helped fund a=
 new ALS drug [ https://substack.com/redirect/bb91b7c1-5fab-47bf-8dc9-c4db9=
2c21635?r=3D9p0gt ]
Wynne Davis [ https://substack.com/redirect/ba0e5b49-55eb-4676-aca6-ddac12b=
3925e?r=3D9p0gt ] for NPR
The ALS Association said  [ https://substack.com/redirect/02812ea3-435e-4bb=
0-bfb2-4f529e81a862?r=3D9p0gt ]that $2.2 million of funds that were raised =
from the Ice Bucket Challenge went into funding the development and trial o=
f the new drug that the Food and Drug Administration approved  [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/2900c3cf-8303-4711-96e4-264ceb7cdc7a?r=3D9p0gt ]this we=
ek for treatment of ALS, which is also known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
Remember the Ice Bucket Challenge?=20
It=E2=80=99s easy to forget the positives of social media. Teen depression =
and suicide, cyberbullying, spreading of false information, and general dis=
connection from the =E2=80=9Creal world.=E2=80=9D These are all very seriou=
s issues for which, rightfully, social media companies have been taken to t=
ask over the past few years. And the benefits of social media =E2=80=94 wha=
t are they again? Connecting with loved ones? Access to information? These =
seem less like "benefits=E2=80=9D and more just table stakes for the world =
we live in today. Social media has become so entrenched, that its benefits =
are hard to discern from everyday life. We expect these things. I am sure t=
here is a name for this bias =E2=80=94 bad things standout as bad and good =
things become expected =E2=80=94 but it escapes me.
So it=E2=80=99s rare that we=E2=80=99re able to so clearly connect the dots=
 between a social media phenomena and a positive outcome. The ALS Ice Bucke=
t Challenge is one such instance: the money raised during the challenge bac=
k in 2014 actually went directly (as far as we can tell) towards developing=
 a drug that can help treat ALS. The new treatment, which was approved by t=
he FDA this week, does not cure ALS but it does slow down the effects.
The novel idea of a viral online challenge to raise money and awareness for=
 a specific cause is, of course, no longer novel. Imagine getting a Faceboo=
k notification that your classmate from 6th grade who you haven=E2=80=99t t=
alked to in a nearly two decades tagged you in a =E2=80=9CXYZ Viral Challen=
ge=E2=80=9D today =E2=80=94 it might be the final straw that pushes you to =
finally delete the app. But we=E2=80=99ll always have those simpler interne=
t times of 2014 to look back on, and new ways of harnessing technology for =
fun and good to look forward to.
(5) I come bringing good news about hydrogen [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/a6687f6d-cfb1-4acd-b5b1-84e397b9579b?r=3D9p0gt ]
Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/ecb7197e-d319-4707-85c8-af208ebd=
fb5f?r=3D9p0gt ] for Noahpinion
Notice that all of these uses have one thing in common =E2=80=94 they=E2=80=
=99re all ways of replacing fossil fuels for things we already do. Tons of =
things in our economy rely on burning stuff; hydrogen is simply a flammable=
 chemical that doesn=E2=80=99t release carbon when you burn it. This is why=
 my optimism about green hydrogen is a lot more moderate and tempered than =
my optimism about batteries =E2=80=94 whereas batteries enable us to do lot=
s of things we can=E2=80=99t currently do at all, green hydrogen pretty muc=
h just replaces things we already know how to do.
Noah Smith starts out his essay on green hydrogen, writing, =E2=80=9Cthis i=
s a techno-optimist blog, and it=E2=80=99s time for another techno-optimist=
 post.=E2=80=9D Well, Noah, the Weekly Dose of Optimism is a blog about tec=
hno-optimist blogs, so if you=E2=80=99re going to keep producing fantastic =
techno-optimists posts, we=E2=80=99re going to keep covering them =F0=9F=A4=
=9D.
The central observation behind the article is that green hydrogen is follow=
ing a similar =E2=80=9Clearning curve=E2=80=9D to solar, wind, and battery =
technologies. The technologies have been getting cheaper, and as they=E2=80=
=99ve gotten cheaper, we=E2=80=99ve built more of them, which makes them ev=
en cheaper. Learning curves are seemingly harder to spot than you=E2=80=99d=
 think and most people had written off hydrogen =E2=80=94 but curve don=E2=
=80=99t lie. Sure, hydrogen might not power cars (although Terraform and ot=
hers are working on making clean fuels using hydrogen [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/72a2e0fe-ec0c-4006-9950-e52b1a535521?r=3D9p0gt ]) but green hydr=
ogen energy can replace many other activities we already do using fossil fu=
els. In an era of energy abundance, we=E2=80=99ll need some forms of energy=
 to unlock whole new capabilities (like batteries) while others will just n=
eed to make existing activities greener (like hydrogen.)
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you enjoyed this week=E2=80=99s email,=
 please share it with a friend or two!
I=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am EST on Monday morning. Enjoy the wee=
kend.
Packy

