size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The central obser=
vation behind the article is that green hydrogen is following a similar &#8=
220;learning curve&#8221; to solar, wind, and battery technologies. The tec=
hnologies have been getting cheaper, and as they&#8217;ve gotten cheaper, w=
e&#8217;ve built more of them, which makes them even cheaper. Learning curv=
es are seemingly harder to spot than you&#8217;d think and most people had =
written off hydrogen &#8212; but curve don&#8217;t lie. Sure, hydrogen migh=
t not power cars (</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/72a2e0fe-=
ec0c-4006-9950-e52b1a535521?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; te=
xt-decoration: underline;">although Terraform and others are working on mak=
ing clean fuels using hydrogen</a><span>) but green hydrogen energy can rep=
lace many other activities we already do using fossil fuels. In an era of e=
nergy abundance, we&#8217;ll need some forms of energy to unlock whole new =
capabilities (like batteries) while others will just need to make existing =
activities greener (like hydrogen.)</span></p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px=
